'''Bettina''' is a vanished community founded in 1847 by German immigrants as part of the [[Adelsverein]] colonization of the [[Fisher-Miller Land Grant]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]]. It was located on the banks of the [[Llano River]] in [[Llano County, Texas|Llano County]], and no trace of the settlement remains today.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lich|first=Gene E|title=Bettina, Texas|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hvb55|work=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> The community was named after German artist and social activist [[Bettina von Arnim]] and was one of five attempted by the [[Darmstadt Forty]]. It was also known as the ''Darmstaedter Kolonie''. The community was sponsored by the [[Adelsverein]], and founded on idealistic philosophies of European freethinkers of the day. It is notable for the community's [[camaraderie]] and mutually respectful relations with local indigenous tribes. Lack of a formal community framework caused Bettina to fail within a year of its founding.
==History== The colony had its beginnings in 1846 in [[Darmstadt]], [[Giessen]], and [[Heidelberg]], where [[Prince Carl of Solms-Braunfels]] delivered speeches on behalf of the Adelsverein, promoting [[Texas]] as a [[utopian]] frontier for university graduates. The Darmstadt Forty was a [[Freethought|freethinker]] organization founded by [[Hermann Spiess]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Ragsdale|first=Crystal Sasse|title=Hermann Spiess|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fsp11|work=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|accessdate=18 January 2012}}</ref> [[Ferdinand Ludwig Herff]],<ref name="Ferdinand Ludwig Herff">{{cite web|last=Stembridge|first=Vernie A|title=Ferdinand Ludwig Herff|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fhe27|work=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|accessdate=18 January 2012}}</ref> and [[Gustav Schleicher]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Heinen|first=Hubert Plummer|title=Gustav Schleicher|url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fsc09|work=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|accessdate=18 January 2012}}</ref> and based on ideals of [[Étienne Cabet]] and [[Charles Fourier]]. The Darmstadt Forty group set sail with dogs, goods, supplies, and an array of musical instruments aboard the ''St. Pauli'' from [[Hamburg]] in April 1847, arriving in [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]] on July 17. From Galveston they sailed to [[Indianola, Texas|Indianola]], where Adelsverein Commissioner-General [[John O. Meusebach]] had arranged for numerous wagons to haul the group and its freight inland. They were paid $10,000 in gold to help finance the first year of their settlement. During the four weeks it took them to travel to [[New Braunfels, Texas|New Braunfels]], the trek took on the ambiance of a collegiate party, with beer and singing and youthful high spiritedness filling the journey.<ref name="Reinhardt">{{cite journal|last=Reinhardt|first=Louis|title=The Communistic Colony of Bettina|journal=The Quarterly of the Texas State Historical Association|year=1900|volume=3|pages=33–40|url=http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth101015/m1/41/|location=Denton, TX|publisher=Texas State Historical Association}}</ref>
Spiess and Meusebach scouted the area of the Llano River and chose the location for Bettina.<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=Irene Marschall|title=John O.Meusebach|year=1967| publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-73656-6|page=121}}</ref> Member Louis Reinhardt described the Llano River as so pure and crystal clear they named it the Silvery Llano. Upon reaching the site of Bettina, the group unloaded their musical instruments and began to sing their favorite songs. An adobe house was constructed with an outer siding of 10,000 shingles carved from a single pecan tree. The house was topped with a weather vane made by August Strauss.<ref name="Reinhardt"/>
As made possible in part by the [[Meusebach–Comanche Treaty]], the group's interactions with local indigenous tribes were cordial. Reinhardt listed seven tribes among the colony's visitors: [[Comanche]], [[Lipan Apache people|Lipan Apache]], [[Waco tribe|Waco]], [[Lenape|Delaware]], [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]], [[Choctaw]] and [[Shawnee]]. The colonists and the tribes shared food and goods, and tried to learn each other's languages. Reinhardt claimed that the indigenous people usually gave back three times more than the colonists gave them.<ref name="Reinhardt"/>
The downfall of the colony was brought about by its own ideals of having a community not regulated by authority figures. Conflicts arose between individuals over who would shoulder the bulk of the workload. Only one crop ever came to fruition, which was 200 bushels of corn. After the Adelsverein's funding ran out, members of the group gradually drifted elsewhere.<ref name="Reinhardt"/>
