{{Cleanup-tone|date=November 2017}} '''Scientific communism''' was one of the three major elements of [[Marxism–Leninism]] as taught in the [[Soviet Union]] in all institutions of [[higher education]] and pursued in the corresponding research institutions and departments.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tZHCAQAAQBAJ|title=Encyclopaedia of Contemporary Russian|last=Oznobkina|first=Elena|date=28 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781136787867|location=|pages=548|language=en|chapter=Scientific Communism (Nauchnyi kommunizm)}}</ref> The discipline consisted in investigation of laws, patterns, ways and forms of [[class struggle]], [[socialist revolution]] and development of [[socialism]] and construction of [[communism]].
== Overview == Passing exams in scientific communism was an obligatory prerequisite in obtaining any [[postgraduate]] scientific degree in the Soviet Union (see "[[Kandidat]]" for details).
Typical courses of study included the following topics, among others: * [[History of communism|Origins and development of the communist theory]] * Theory of [[socialist revolution]] * [[Proletarian internationalism|International communist movement]] * [[Dictatorship of the proletariat]] * Transformation of [[socialism]] into [[communism]] * [[Democratic centralism]] * Communist interpersonal relations and upbringing * Criticisms of [[anti-communism]]
== Other components of Marxism–Leninism == * Marxist–Leninist philosophy, subdivided into [[dialectical materialism]] and [[historical materialism]] * [[Political economy]], subdivided into the political economy of capitalism and political economy of socialism
